Ibid. Atoms; 

                     〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                  , Things so minute and small, that they were incapable of division into lesser Particles, of whose blind and fortuitous Concourse, Epicurus and Democritus fancied the Glorious Universe to have been made; a Whimsy so ill agreeing with our Author's Philosophy, that he has allowed their Atoms a very different Place from any in Nature, esteeming them aright, the Offspring and Subjects of blind Ignorance, and black Confusion.

