V. 298. Asphaltic Slime; 

                     〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                  , Gr. Clay taken out of the Lake Asphaltites, a clammy Substance, a sort of natural Mortar extreamly viscous and binding. Josephus tells us, this Lake is near the Land of Sodom, and that this black Bitumen floats in it (for few things sink there) in great lumps, like Bulls without Heads, so strangely tough and clammy, that the Boats which bring it on shore are scarce able to disengage themselves from the glutinous, surprising Surface of the Lake. Bo. 5. c. 5. See Bo. 2. v. 411.

